The “Moats” (Most Dangerous Active Patents)
Within the 100‑patent slices, here are the 3–5 live families most likely to constrain a topical, epigenetic regenerative medicine program.

1. EP 1 418 949 B1 / WO 2003‑012051 – “INHIBITOR OF DNA METHYLATION” (zebularine core)
Owners: Oregon State, US Government (HHS), Univ. Southern California, Univ. Miami.

What it covers:

2‑pyrimidinone derivatives (incl. zebularine) as C5‑cytosine DNA‑methyltransferase inhibitors.

Use claims for treating methylation‑linked conditions (cancer, epigenetic diseases), plus compositions and kits.

Threat to you:

In countries where this family is still in force, any claim drafted broadly to “use of zebularine for inhibiting DNA methylation in a mammal” or “treating methylation‑linked disease” could read on your indication if you rely solely on the hypomethylation mechanism, even for topical use.

If the family is close to or at term in your key markets, the moat is shrinking, but you must confirm term and SPC/PTE on a per‑jurisdiction basis.

2. WO 2008‑147283 / EP 2 164 500 – “USE OF ZEBULARINE FOR THE TREATMENT OF AUTOIMMUNE DISEASES OR IMMUNE REJECTION OF TRANSPLANTS”
Owners: Salford, Sjögren, Widegren / Idogen AB.

Core claims:

Use of zebularine (and close analogues) to increase IDO, induce immunological tolerance, and treat autoimmune disease or prevent rejection of transplants.

Relevance to topical regenerative therapy:

If your wound‑healing product relies on local immune tolerance (e.g., modulating T‑cell responses in chronic ulcers) and you emphasize IDO‑mediated tolerance, some claims may be arguable prior art or even overlapping.

However, these patents are framed around systemic/tolerance endpoints, not cosmetic or local regenerative indications; careful claim drafting (e.g., “enhancing re‑epithelialization and scar quality” rather than “treating autoimmune disease”) can help you design around.

3. Dental pulp / hard‑tissue epigenetic patents (WO 2015‑037945; KR 2015‑0031210; WO 2010‑052814)
Owners: SNU R&DB Foundation; Nihon University.

Core claims:

Pharmaceutical compositions for dental pulp regenerative therapy and apexification comprising prolyl hydroxylase inhibitors or HDAC inhibitors plus antibiotics in a synthetic polymer nanofiber mesh.

Composition for hard tissue regenerative therapy using specific bacteria (S. mutans, P. gingivalis) at low concentrations.

Why they matter:

They demonstrate the patent offices’ comfort with claiming local delivery of epigenetic modulators for regenerative endpoints, which examiners may cite against your topical claims as analogous art.

Overlap is mostly mechanistic (epigenetic modulation for local regeneration), not on your specific target compound; nevertheless, they narrow room for “generic epigenetic topical for tissue regeneration” language.

4. EP 3 936 188 B1 – “CELLS FOR REGENERATIVE THERAPY” (chromatin methylation in cardiac cells)
Owner: University of Washington.

Core claims:

Methods of regulating cardiac myocyte cell‑cycle exit via histone methylation modifications; cell preparations with defined epigenetic states for cardiac repair.

Threat profile:

Highly organ‑specific (heart) and cell‑therapy focused, but it stakes out “histone methylation as a lever for regeneration” in a broad conceptual way.

Examiners may view your zebularine topical epigenetic claims as an obvious extension of this paradigm unless you differentiate clearly in indication (skin/wound), drug class (nucleoside vs. enzyme‑targeting small molecules), and delivery (topical vs. systemic/cellular).

5. Biovaxim EP 1 748 792 B1 – “Compositions comprising demethylating agents as enhancers of immunotherapy”
Owner: Biovaxim Ltd.

Core claims:

Demethylating agents (including DNA‑methylation inhibitors) co‑administered with immunotherapeutic agents to treat chronic infections and neoplasia.

Impact:

If you ever combine your topical epigenetic with local immune therapies (e.g., oncolytic or vaccine‑like components in skin cancers), you will need to navigate these claims.

For pure wound healing/regeneration without an immunotherapy component, exposure is lower.

FTO Verdict: Red Ocean vs. Blue Ocean
Within the 100‑patent snapshots you provided, the picture is:

Where it is “red” (congested)
