Practical Strategy Recommendations
Within the constraints of these 100‑patent slices (not a full global search), I would steer your strategy as follows:

Own the topical formulation layer.

Draft claims on specific dermal vehicles (e.g., hydrogel, spray, coated dressings) that enable high local zebularine exposure with minimal systemic uptake.

Emphasize kinetic features (e.g., controlled release profiles) and wound‑bed pharmacodynamics that are not described in oncology/autoimmune zebularine art.

Anchor your indication in skin regeneration, not systemic immunology.

Center claims on re‑epithelialization, collagen organization, and scar quality rather than “treating autoimmune disease” or “inducing tolerance,” to distance from Salford/Idogen and Biovaxim families.

Design around remaining moats.

Avoid claim language that simply recites “inhibiting DNA methylation to treat disease” without added dermal specifics; that language is heavily owned by the Oregon/US‑government family.

If you rely on IDO as a biomarker, define a local, transient, wound‑bed effect rather than systemic tolerance, and consider alternative mechanistic markers (e.g., fetal‑like methylome patterns) that are less encumbered.

Exploit the graveyard.

Use expired zebularine and regeneration patents as defensive publications to keep competitors from re‑patenting obvious variants.

Cite them to argue obviousness against any third party trying to claim broad “epigenetic agent + regeneration” without your specific formulation twist.

